text: Galkovsky LiveJournal blogposts are wild because the guy whose grandfather was the Soviet soldier who captured Puyi will just be down there in the comment section trying to argue about historical details with signed silk envelope letters and awards from Mao and Chiang Kai-shek

And the grandson's own blog is posting news about riots erupting in various countries and comparing it with news about solar magnetic storms trying to prove there's a relation between sun cycles/solar weather and societal changes/revolutions. The Russian internet is incredible...

A lot of the side effects of GLP-1 agonists like Zogzempic that people fearmonger over are just the side effects of any big weight loss, stuff like fasting also massively destroys muscle in people who don't train, Haidut/Georgi Dinkov had some great interviews on losing weight...

Ppl just assume losing weight naturally through exercise and dieting is 100% healthy because of cultural reasons but it's pretty obviously stressful for the organism to shed 20 kilograms of fat, any side effects of appetite suppression would not be too diff from natural fat loss.

I can't think of a mechanism other than ppl dipping into hypoglycemia so evne if it's real it's probably easy to avoid if ppl titrate properly and check their blood sugar but it's probably a fake study because they've been on the market for a while and it hasn't been a concern

I think you can see some contemporary figures like Aleksandr Dugin as similar "masonic obscurantists" (even though for most it's probably unintentional and just intellectual naivety...) It also hints at what the counter-initiation truly fears, which is not religious obscurantism.

E.g. what is dangerous to the anti-religious forces of freemasonry or their current equivalents is not some folk mysticism and primitivism, but a powerful conservative state with well-developed legal system, philosophy in the universities, etc. Basically Leibniz and not Tolstoy.
